The new species has no remarkable external differences from other members of the genus in the antemedial series of three large dark spots (fourth small dark spot presented near tornus in 
<taxonomicName id="4C3C4D5ED36BFFCCFB55FC55DB47FC56" authority="Bayarsaikhan &amp; Cha &amp; Černý &amp; Kwon &amp; Bae, 2022" authorityName="Bayarsaikhan &amp; Cha &amp; Černý &amp; Kwon &amp; Bae" authorityYear="2022" box="[1157,1288,902,928]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Stictane" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="489" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="trigonica" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis id="B948EACFD36BFFCCFB55FC55DB47FC56" box="[1157,1288,902,928]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="489">S. trigonica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="B948EACFD36BFFCCFADEFC55DB03FC56" bold="true" box="[1294,1356,902,928]" pageId="8" pageNumber="489">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A27B57B4D36BFFCCFADEFC55DB03FC56" box="[1294,1356,902,928]" pageId="8" pageNumber="489" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
), more or less curved dark medial band, 1–3 discoidal dark spots (two dark spots in 
<taxonomicName id="4C3C4D5ED36BFFCCFBD1FC79DAC9FC32" authority="Bayarsaikhan &amp; Cha &amp; Černý &amp; Kwon &amp; Bae, 2022" authorityName="Bayarsaikhan &amp; Cha &amp; Černý &amp; Kwon &amp; Bae" authorityYear="2022" box="[1025,1158,938,964]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Stictane" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="489" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="trigonica" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis id="B948EACFD36BFFCCFBD1FC79DAC9FC32" box="[1025,1158,938,964]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="489">S. trigonica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="B948EACFD36BFFCCFB5DFC79DA81FC32" bold="true" box="[1165,1230,938,964]" pageId="8" pageNumber="489">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A27B57B4D36BFFCCFB5DFC79DA81FC32" box="[1165,1230,938,964]" pageId="8" pageNumber="489" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
, figs 7a, b), and a curved postdiscal series of dark small spots of whitish forewing.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B8336DDD36BFFCCFF17FC21DDB1F9BB" blockId="8.[151,1437,721,2008]" pageId="8" pageNumber="489">
According the subapical spine on outer margin of cucullus in male genitalia, the present new species is similar to 
<taxonomicName id="4C3C4D5ED36BFFCCFF65FBC5DFB0FBC6" authority="(Snellen, 1880)" baseAuthorityName="Snellen" baseAuthorityYear="1880" box="[181,511,1046,1072]" class="Insecta" family="Nolidae" genus="Manoba" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="489" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fractilinea">
<emphasis id="B948EACFD36BFFCCFF65FBC5DF08FBC6" box="[181,327,1046,1072]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="489">S. fractilinea</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFAD4B2CD36BFFCCFE87FBC5DFB8FBC6" author="Snellen, P. C. T." box="[343,503,1046,1072]" pageId="8" pageNumber="489" pagination="92" refId="ref6946" refString="Snellen, P. C. T. (1880) Lepidoptera. In: Veth, P. J. (Ed.), Midden Sumatra, 4 (8), pp. 92." type="journal article" year="1880">Snellen, 1880</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="4C3C4D5ED36BFFCCFDDBFBC5DD7FFBC6" authority="Holloway, 2001" authorityName="Holloway" authorityYear="2001" box="[523,816,1046,1072]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Stictane" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="489" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="muara">
<emphasis id="B948EACFD36BFFCCFDDBFBC5DC3EFBC6" box="[523,625,1046,1072]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="489">S. muara</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EFAD4B2CD36BFFCCFDAAFBC5DD7FFBC6" author="Holloway, J. D." box="[634,816,1046,1072]" pageId="8" pageNumber="489" pagination="279 - 486" refId="ref6724" refString="Holloway, J. D. (2001) The Moths of Borneo: Family Arctiidae, Subfamily Lithosiinae. Malayan Nature Journal, 7, 279 - 486." type="journal article" year="2001">Holloway, 2001</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="4C3C4D5ED36BFFCCFCECFBC5DAB6FBC6" authority="Bayarsaikhan &amp; Bae, 2019" authorityName="Bayarsaikhan &amp; Bae" authorityYear="2019" box="[828,1273,1046,1072]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Stictane" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="489" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="heppneri">
<emphasis id="B948EACFD36BFFCCFCECFBC5DDF2FBC6" box="[828,957,1046,1072]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="489">S. heppneri</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EFAD4B2CD36BFFCCFC15FBC5DAB6FBC6" author="Bayarsaikhan, U. &amp; Im, K. H. &amp; Bae, Y. S." box="[965,1273,1046,1072]" pageId="8" pageNumber="489" pagination="253 - 263" refId="ref6178" refString="Bayarsaikhan, U., Im, K. H. &amp; Bae, Y. S. (2019) Two new species and a newly recorded species of the genus Stictane Hampson (Lepidoptera, Erebidae, Arctiinae) from Cambodia. Zootaxa, 4686 (2), 253 - 263. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4686.2.5" type="journal article" year="2019">Bayarsaikhan &amp; Bae, 2019</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName id="4C3C4D5ED36BFFCCFAE5FBC5DFE2FBA2" authority="Bucsek, 2020" authorityName="Bucsek" authorityYear="2020" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Stictane" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="489" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bayarsaikhanae">
<emphasis id="B948EACFD36BFFCCFAE5FBC5DF46FBA2" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="489">S. bayarsaikhanae</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EFAD4B2CD36BFFCCFEC0FBE9DFE2FBA2" author="Bucsek, K." box="[272,429,1082,1108]" pageId="8" pageNumber="489" pagination="19 - 46" refId="ref6450" refString="Bucsek, K. (2020) Contribution to the knowledge of Lithosiini (Erebidae, Arctiinae) of Central and Northern Laos. Part 3. En- tomofauna carpathica, 32 (2), 19 - 46." type="journal article" year="2020">Bucsek, 2020</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
. But the new species can be distinguished from those similar species by the short (shorter than apex of uncus), roundly stout valva with a short subapical spine on outer margin of cucullus medially, it is above the tip of saccular spine, and aedeagus vesica has an area of thin, diverse sized spines and one large-wrinkled spine. In 
<taxonomicName id="4C3C4D5ED36BFFCCFF2EFB75DFC0FB36" baseAuthorityName="Snellen" baseAuthorityYear="1880" box="[254,399,1190,1216]" class="Insecta" family="Nolidae" genus="Manoba" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="489" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fractilinea">
<emphasis id="B948EACFD36BFFCCFF2EFB75DFC0FB36" box="[254,399,1190,1216]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="489">S. fractilinea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, slender valva is longer than apex of uncus, with a short (almost same size to 
<taxonomicName id="4C3C4D5ED36BFFCCFB22FB75DB3BFB36" authority="Bayarsaikhan &amp; Cha &amp; Černý &amp; Kwon &amp; Bae, 2022" authorityName="Bayarsaikhan &amp; Cha &amp; Černý &amp; Kwon &amp; Bae" authorityYear="2022" box="[1266,1396,1190,1216]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Stictane" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="489" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="trigonica" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis id="B948EACFD36BFFCCFB22FB75DB3BFB36" box="[1266,1396,1190,1216]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="489">S. trigonica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="B948EACFD36BFFCCFAABFB75DEE1FB12" bold="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="489">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A27B57B4D36BFFCCFAABFB75DEE1FB12" pageId="8" pageNumber="489" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
) subapical spine on outer margin of cucullus, it is arising immediately near the tip of saccular spine, and aedeagus vesica has a bundle of thin spines and a straight larger one (
<bibRefCitation id="EFAD4B2CD36BFFCCFCFBFB3DDDB2FAFE" author="Kirti, J. S. &amp; Joshi, R. &amp; Singh, N." box="[811,1021,1262,1288]" pageId="8" pageNumber="489" pagination="1 - 7" refId="ref6754" refString="Kirti, J. S., Joshi, R. &amp; Singh, N. (2013) Taxonomic studies and new faunistic records of two species of the genus Stictane Hampson (Lepidoptera: Erebidae: Arctiinae) from India. Acta Zoologica Cracoviensia, 56 (1), 1 - 7. https: // doi. org / 10.3409 / azc. 56 _ 1.01" type="journal article" year="2013">
Kirti 
<emphasis id="B948EACFD36BFFCCFCB9FB3CDDEFFAFE" box="[873,928,1262,1288]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="489">et al.</emphasis>
2013: 4
</bibRefCitation>
, figs 4–7). In 
<taxonomicName id="4C3C4D5ED36BFFCCFB47FB3DDAB3FAFE" authorityName="Holloway" authorityYear="2001" box="[1175,1276,1262,1288]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Stictane" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="489" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="muara">
<emphasis id="B948EACFD36BFFCCFB47FB3DDAB3FAFE" box="[1175,1276,1262,1288]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="489">S. muara</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, stout valva is shorter than apex of uncus, with a long (almost four times longer than 
<taxonomicName id="4C3C4D5ED36BFFCCFC61FAC1DA7BFADA" authority="Bayarsaikhan &amp; Cha &amp; Černý &amp; Kwon &amp; Bae, 2022" authorityName="Bayarsaikhan &amp; Cha &amp; Černý &amp; Kwon &amp; Bae" authorityYear="2022" box="[945,1076,1298,1324]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Stictane" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="489" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="trigonica" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis id="B948EACFD36BFFCCFC61FAC1DA7BFADA" box="[945,1076,1298,1324]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="489">S. trigonica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="B948EACFD36BFFCCFBEBFAC1DA34FADA" bold="true" box="[1083,1147,1298,1324]" pageId="8" pageNumber="489">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A27B57B4D36BFFCCFBEBFAC1DA34FADA" box="[1083,1147,1298,1324]" pageId="8" pageNumber="489" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
) subapical spine on outer margin of cucullus, it is arising immediately near the tip of saccular spine, and aedeagus vesica with numerous cornuti (
<bibRefCitation id="EFAD4B2CD36BFFCCFF02FA89DFF2FA82" author="Holloway, J. D." box="[210,445,1370,1396]" pageId="8" pageNumber="489" pagination="279 - 486" refId="ref6724" refString="Holloway, J. D. (2001) The Moths of Borneo: Family Arctiidae, Subfamily Lithosiinae. Malayan Nature Journal, 7, 279 - 486." type="journal article" year="2001">Holloway 2001: 418</bibRefCitation>
, figs 8d-e). In 
<taxonomicName id="4C3C4D5ED36BFFCCFDB2FA89DCADFA82" authorityName="Bayarsaikhan &amp; Bae" authorityYear="2019" box="[610,738,1370,1396]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Stictane" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="489" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="heppneri">
<emphasis id="B948EACFD36BFFCCFDB2FA89DCADFA82" box="[610,738,1370,1396]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="489">S. heppneri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, stout valva is shorter than apex of uncus, with a long (almost two times longer than 
<taxonomicName id="4C3C4D5ED36BFFCCFE40FAADDC5CFA6E" authority="Bayarsaikhan &amp; Cha &amp; Černý &amp; Kwon &amp; Bae, 2022" authorityName="Bayarsaikhan &amp; Cha &amp; Černý &amp; Kwon &amp; Bae" authorityYear="2022" box="[400,531,1406,1432]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Stictane" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="489" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="trigonica" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis id="B948EACFD36BFFCCFE40FAADDC5CFA6E" box="[400,531,1406,1432]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="489">S. trigonica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="B948EACFD36BFFCCFDCAFAADDC16FA6E" bold="true" box="[538,601,1406,1432]" pageId="8" pageNumber="489">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A27B57B4D36BFFCCFDCAFAADDC16FA6E" box="[538,601,1406,1432]" pageId="8" pageNumber="489" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
) subapical spine on outer margin of cucullus, it is above the tip of saccular spine, and aedeagus vesica has two bundles of thin, short spines and a long, slender, strongly waved one (
<bibRefCitation id="EFAD4B2CD36BFFCCFA9FFA71DFE8FA16" author="Bayarsaikhan, U. &amp; Im, K. H. &amp; Bae, Y. S." pageId="8" pageNumber="489" pagination="253 - 263" refId="ref6178" refString="Bayarsaikhan, U., Im, K. H. &amp; Bae, Y. S. (2019) Two new species and a newly recorded species of the genus Stictane Hampson (Lepidoptera, Erebidae, Arctiinae) from Cambodia. Zootaxa, 4686 (2), 253 - 263. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4686.2.5" type="journal article" year="2019">
Bayarsaikhan 
<emphasis id="B948EACFD36BFFCCFF24FA14DF63FA16" box="[244,300,1478,1504]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="489">et al.</emphasis>
2019: 260
</bibRefCitation>
, fig 24a-b). In 
<taxonomicName id="4C3C4D5ED36BFFCCFD9EFA15DD51FA16" authorityName="Bucsek" authorityYear="2020" box="[590,798,1478,1504]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Stictane" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="489" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bayarsaikhanae">
<emphasis id="B948EACFD36BFFCCFD9EFA15DD51FA16" box="[590,798,1478,1504]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="489">S. bayarsaikhanae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, slender valva is shorter than apex of uncus, with a short (almost same size to 
<taxonomicName id="4C3C4D5ED36BFFCCFE53FA39DC49F9F2" authority="Bayarsaikhan &amp; Cha &amp; Černý &amp; Kwon &amp; Bae, 2022" authorityName="Bayarsaikhan &amp; Cha &amp; Černý &amp; Kwon &amp; Bae" authorityYear="2022" box="[387,518,1514,1540]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Stictane" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="489" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="trigonica" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis id="B948EACFD36BFFCCFE53FA39DC49F9F2" box="[387,518,1514,1540]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="489">S. trigonica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="B948EACFD36BFFCCFDDDFA39DC02F9F2" bold="true" box="[525,589,1514,1540]" pageId="8" pageNumber="489">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A27B57B4D36BFFCCFDDDFA39DC02F9F2" box="[525,589,1514,1540]" pageId="8" pageNumber="489" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
) subapical spine on outer margin of cucullus, it is arising immediately near the tip of saccular spine, and aedeagus vesica has a bundle of thin, same sized spines and a weakly waved, larger one (
<bibRefCitation id="EFAD4B2CD36BFFCCFF1EF9E1DFC0F9BA" author="Bucsek, K." box="[206,399,1586,1612]" pageId="8" pageNumber="489" pagination="19 - 46" refId="ref6450" refString="Bucsek, K. (2020) Contribution to the knowledge of Lithosiini (Erebidae, Arctiinae) of Central and Northern Laos. Part 3. En- tomofauna carpathica, 32 (2), 19 - 46." type="journal article" year="2020">Bucsek 2020: 44</bibRefCitation>
, figs 89–92, Bayarsaikhan 
<emphasis id="B948EACFD36BFFCCFD6FF9E0DCB8F9BA" box="[703,759,1586,1612]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="489">et al.</emphasis>
2021: 142, figs 14a-b).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B8336DDD36BFFCCFF17F985DDEEF8BE" blockId="8.[151,1437,721,2008]" pageId="8" pageNumber="489">
The female genitalia structure of the present new species is similar to 
<taxonomicName id="4C3C4D5ED36BFFCCFC21F985DB71F986" authority="(De Joannis, 1928)" baseAuthorityName="De Joannis" baseAuthorityYear="1928" box="[1009,1342,1622,1648]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Stictane" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="489" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="munda">
<emphasis id="B948EACFD36BFFCCFC21F985DA14F986" box="[1009,1115,1622,1648]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="489">S. munda</emphasis>
(De Joannis, 1928)
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFAD4B2CD36BFFCCFA9FF985DFE5F962" author="Bayarsaikhan, U. &amp; Bae, Y. S." pageId="8" pageNumber="489" pagination="87 - 92" refId="ref6123" refString="Bayarsaikhan, U. &amp; Bae, Y. S. (2021) The genus Stictane Hampson, 1900 (Lepidoptera: Erebidae: Arctiinae) in Vietnam. Journal of Asia-Pacific Biodiversity, 14, 87 - 92. https: // doi. org / 10.1016 / j. japb. 2020.12.004" type="journal article" year="2021">Bayarsaikhan &amp; Bae 2021: 91</bibRefCitation>
, fig. 4B), and 
<taxonomicName id="4C3C4D5ED36BFFCCFD9DF9A9DA3DF962" authority="Chen, Hsu, Chen &amp; Buchsbaum, 2018" authorityName="Chen, Hsu, Chen &amp; Buchsbaum" authorityYear="2018" box="[589,1138,1658,1684]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Stictane" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="489" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="imorod">
<emphasis id="B948EACFD36BFFCCFD9DF9A9DCF5F962" box="[589,698,1658,1684]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="489">S. imorod</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EFAD4B2CD36BFFCCFD11F9A9DA3DF962" author="Chen, D. J. &amp; Hsu, L. P. &amp; Chen, M. Y. &amp; Buchsbaum, U." box="[705,1138,1658,1684]" pageId="8" pageNumber="489" pagination="39 - 42" refId="ref6524" refString="Chen, D. J., Hsu, L. P., Chen, M. Y. &amp; Buchsbaum, U. (2018) Stictane imorod sp. n. from Lanyu Island (Taiwan) (Insecta, Lepidoptera: Erebidae, Arctiinae, Lithosiini) Contribution to the moths of Taiwan 13. Mitteilungen der Muncher Entomologischen Gesellschaft, 108, 39 - 42." type="journal article" year="2018">Chen, Hsu, Chen &amp; Buchsbaum, 2018</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFAD4B2CD36BFFCCFB51F9A9DB25F962" author="Chen, D. J. &amp; Hsu, L. P. &amp; Chen, M. Y. &amp; Buchsbaum, U." box="[1153,1386,1658,1684]" pageId="8" pageNumber="489" pagination="39 - 42" refId="ref6524" refString="Chen, D. J., Hsu, L. P., Chen, M. Y. &amp; Buchsbaum, U. (2018) Stictane imorod sp. n. from Lanyu Island (Taiwan) (Insecta, Lepidoptera: Erebidae, Arctiinae, Lithosiini) Contribution to the moths of Taiwan 13. Mitteilungen der Muncher Entomologischen Gesellschaft, 108, 39 - 42." type="journal article" year="2018">Chen et al. 2018: 41</bibRefCitation>
, fig. 4). But the new species can be distinguished from two other species by the globular corpus bursae membranous and bent appendix bursae strongly sclerotized whole of length. In 
<emphasis id="B948EACFD36BFFCCFCADF911DDA3F92A" box="[893,1004,1730,1756]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="489">
<taxonomicName id="4C3C4D5ED36BFFCCFCADF911DDA7F92A" baseAuthorityName="De Joannis" baseAuthorityYear="1928" box="[893,1000,1730,1756]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Stictane" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="489" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="munda">S. munda</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
corpus bursae is irregularly ovoid and strongly sclerotized, except membranous medial area, and membranous appendix bursae with strongly sclerotized plate in cervix area. In 
<emphasis id="B948EACFD36BFFCCFE71F8D9DC5AF8D2" box="[417,533,1802,1828]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="489">
<taxonomicName id="4C3C4D5ED36BFFCCFE71F8D9DC5EF8D2" authorityName="Chen, Hsu, Chen &amp; Buchsbaum" authorityYear="2018" box="[417,529,1802,1828]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Stictane" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="489" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="imorod">S. imorod</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
globular, membranous corpus bursae has strongly sclerotized plate, its covered spines and appendix bursae is weakly sclerotized along whole length.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C3266556D36BFFCDFF17F882DCA0FD73" lastPageId="9" lastPageNumber="490" pageId="8" pageNumber="489" type="description">
<paragraph id="8B8336DDD36BFFCDFF17F882DCA0FD73" blockId="8.[151,1437,721,2008]" lastBlockId="9.[151,1437,151,753]" lastPageId="9" lastPageNumber="490" pageId="8" pageNumber="489">
<emphasis id="B948EACFD36BFFCCFF17F882DF16F89D" bold="true" box="[199,345,1873,1899]" pageId="8" pageNumber="489">Description.</emphasis>
<emphasis id="B948EACFD36BFFCCFEB0F881DFD2F89A" box="[352,413,1874,1900]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="489">Adult</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation id="13072A58D36BFFCCFE7CF881DC63F89B" box="[428,556,1874,1901]" captionStart="FIGURES 2–11" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1810,1834]" captionTargetBox="[173,1415,191,1783]" captionTargetId="figure-23@4.[163,1424,181,1787]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 2–11. General view of the body of adults of the genus Stictane from Thailand. 2. S. fractilinea, female (INU˗10364T). 3. S. gemina, male (INU˗10356T). 4. S. mlcochi, male (INU˗10355T). 5a. S. pectenicorniculum, male (OPU˗009T). 5b. ditto, female (OPU˗008T). 6a. S. fuscus, male (OPU˗001T). 6b. ditto, female (OPU˗017T). 7a. S. cambodiensis, male (INU˗10358T). 7b. ditto, female (INU˗10362T). 8a. S. bokorensis, male (OPU˗014T). 8b. ditto, female (OPU˗018M). 9. S. kualabohi, female (INU˗10351T). 10. S. transversana, male (OPU˗015T). 11a. S. trigonica sp. n., male (holotype, INU˗10363T). 11b. ditto, female (paratype, INU˗10353T)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6571783" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6571783/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="489">Figs 11a, b</figureCitation>
). Male and female are superficially similar. Length of forewing 
<quantity id="4CC49B38D36BFFCCFAD0F881DB0EF89A" box="[1280,1345,1874,1900]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.0" pageId="8" pageNumber="489" unit="mm" value="6.0">6 mm</quantity>
in male (
<figureCitation id="13072A58D36BFFCCFF4FF8A5DEBBF866" box="[159,244,1910,1936]" captionStart="FIGURES 2–11" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1810,1834]" captionTargetBox="[173,1415,191,1783]" captionTargetId="figure-23@4.[163,1424,181,1787]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 2–11. General view of the body of adults of the genus Stictane from Thailand. 2. S. fractilinea, female (INU˗10364T). 3. S. gemina, male (INU˗10356T). 4. S. mlcochi, male (INU˗10355T). 5a. S. pectenicorniculum, male (OPU˗009T). 5b. ditto, female (OPU˗008T). 6a. S. fuscus, male (OPU˗001T). 6b. ditto, female (OPU˗017T). 7a. S. cambodiensis, male (INU˗10358T). 7b. ditto, female (INU˗10362T). 8a. S. bokorensis, male (OPU˗014T). 8b. ditto, female (OPU˗018M). 9. S. kualabohi, female (INU˗10351T). 10. S. transversana, male (OPU˗015T). 11a. S. trigonica sp. n., male (holotype, INU˗10363T). 11b. ditto, female (paratype, INU˗10353T)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6571783" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6571783/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="489">Fig 11a</figureCitation>
) and female (
<figureCitation id="13072A58D36BFFCCFE59F8A5DFADF867" box="[393,482,1910,1937]" captionStart="FIGURES 2–11" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1810,1834]" captionTargetBox="[173,1415,191,1783]" captionTargetId="figure-23@4.[163,1424,181,1787]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 2–11. General view of the body of adults of the genus Stictane from Thailand. 2. S. fractilinea, female (INU˗10364T). 3. S. gemina, male (INU˗10356T). 4. S. mlcochi, male (INU˗10355T). 5a. S. pectenicorniculum, male (OPU˗009T). 5b. ditto, female (OPU˗008T). 6a. S. fuscus, male (OPU˗001T). 6b. ditto, female (OPU˗017T). 7a. S. cambodiensis, male (INU˗10358T). 7b. ditto, female (INU˗10362T). 8a. S. bokorensis, male (OPU˗014T). 8b. ditto, female (OPU˗018M). 9. S. kualabohi, female (INU˗10351T). 10. S. transversana, male (OPU˗015T). 11a. S. trigonica sp. n., male (holotype, INU˗10363T). 11b. ditto, female (paratype, INU˗10353T)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6571783" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6571783/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="489">Fig 11b</figureCitation>
). Head and frons pale gray; labial palpus dark, slender, upturned. Patagium, tegula and thorax pale gray. Ground color of forewing pale gray; basal and costal area tinged with fuscous; antemedian series of three large, dark spots distinct and last smaller one indistinct near tornus; dark brown medial band distinctly convex, interrupted or clouded in cell; a pair distinct discoidal dark spots of discal area different sized, which lower one two times bigger than upper; postdiscal series of dark spots curved outward; before apex with one fuscous patch; terminal series of small spots dark. Hindwing fuscous gray; costal and terminal area narrowly fuscous. 
<emphasis id="B948EACFD36AFFCDFB28FF0CDBD2FF0F" box="[1272,1437,223,249]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="490">Male genitalia</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation id="13072A58D36AFFCDFF4FFED0DEA4FEEB" box="[159,235,259,285]" captionStart="FIGURES 12–19" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1816,1840]" captionTargetBox="[154,1416,196,1776]" captionTargetId="figure-20@5.[151,1436,181,1792]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 12–19. Male genitalia of the genus Stictane from Thailand. 12. S. gemina (INU˗10354T). 13. S. mlcochi (INU˗10355T). 14. S. pectenicorniculum (OPU˗009T). 15. S. fuscus (OPU˗016T). 16. S. cambodiensis (INU˗10358T). 17. S. bokorensis (OPU˗014T). 18. S. transversana (INU˗10350T). 19. S. trigonica sp. n. (holotype, INU˗10363T)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6571785" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6571785/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="490">Fig 19</figureCitation>
). Uncus slender, hook˗shaped, with a small spine at tip, same length with tegumen. Tegumen weakly sclerotized. Valva symmetrical, weakly sclerotized whole of length, basal half of valva broader than rounded apical half, its heavily covered with setose; costa with an angled swollen projection medially; slender, curved cucullus with a subapical spine, which almost six times shorter than saccular spine. Sacculus stout, and blunt apical saccular process with a slender, sickle˗shaped spine, that not extend into small spine on outer margin of cucullus. Juxta arched and apical lobe of juxta heart˗shaped. Aedeagus stout and vesica with a large, wrinkled, tapering spine and an area of thin, diverse sized spines, and finely scobinate. 
<emphasis id="B948EACFD36AFFCDFD78FE08DD29FE03" box="[680,870,475,501]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="490">Female genitalia</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation id="13072A58D36AFFCDFCA3FE08DDF1FE03" box="[883,958,475,501]" captionStart="FIGURES 20–26" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1374,1398]" captionTargetBox="[161,1426,195,1336]" captionTargetId="figure-23@6.[151,1436,181,1350]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 20–26. Female genitalia of the genus Stictane from Thailand. 20. S. fractilinea (INU˗10364T). 21. S. pectenicorniculum (OPU˗008T). 22. S. fuscus (OPU˗011T). 23. S. bokorensis (OPU˗018Malaysia). 24. S. trigonica sp. n. (paratype, INU˗10353T). 25. S. kualabohi (INU˗10351T). 26. S. cambodiensis (INU˗10362T)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6571787" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6571787/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="490">Fig 24</figureCitation>
). Papillae anales triangular, weakly sclerotized. Apophyses posteriores about three times as long as apophyses anteriores, both apophyses slender. Ostium broadly waved, weakly sclerotized. Ductus bursae broad funnel-shaped, weakly sclerotized, two times shorter than corpus bursae. Corpus bursae globular, membranous, with a broad area of strongly sclerotized spines in cervix. Bent appendix bursae strongly sclerotized whole of length.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C3266556D36AFFCDFF17FD5DDDC3FD5C" box="[199,908,654,682]" pageId="9" pageNumber="490" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="8B8336DDD36AFFCDFF17FD5DDDC3FD5C" blockId="9.[151,1437,151,753]" box="[199,908,654,682]" pageId="9" pageNumber="490">
<emphasis id="B948EACFD36AFFCDFF17FD5DDF2EFD5E" bold="true" box="[199,353,654,680]" pageId="9" pageNumber="490">Distribution.</emphasis>
SW 
<collectingCountry id="F32B764DD36AFFCDFE47FD5CDFB4FD5F" box="[407,507,655,681]" name="Thailand" pageId="9" pageNumber="490">Thailand</collectingCountry>
(
<collectingRegion id="49F8F83FD36AFFCDFDD9FD5CDCC8FD5F" box="[521,647,655,681]" country="Thailand" name="Chumphon" pageId="9" pageNumber="490">Chumphon</collectingRegion>
and Ranon provinces).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C3266556D36AFFCDFF17FD60DC16FD07" pageId="9" pageNumber="490" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8B8336DDD36AFFCDFF17FD60DC16FD07" blockId="9.[151,1437,151,753]" pageId="9" pageNumber="490">
<emphasis id="B948EACFD36AFFCDFF17FD60DF01FD3B" bold="true" box="[199,334,691,717]" pageId="9" pageNumber="490">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific name is derived from the Latin “ 
<emphasis id="B948EACFD36AFFCDFC88FD60DD85FD3A" box="[856,970,691,716]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="490">trigonicus</emphasis>
” meaning “triangles”, refers to the shape of dark brown medial band of forewing.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
